<font color="#FF0000">FNG'S NEED TO DO READ ARCHIVES</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jun  4 18:14:51 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
The worst thing about this most incredible site is FNG's. Esp. those that post without thought, without reading history, without bothering to scroll back and read prior posts and hard fought dialogues and thinking.  Has any of you &quot;new&quot; to this site bothered to think, and read, and open up your closed and narrow minds, you would see that you are way off base.  But no, you call names, you rant and rave, and behave like children.  <br><br>
Bob Ford posted on 5/20 a story about how he found &quot;his&quot; religion and peace. Bravo Bob, I am glad for you.  I believe  you would have gone to prison rather than Nam if you knew then what you know now. <br><br>
Katherine, (post of 5/25), I agree. Never forget the dead. Of all wars. Yes, even Viet Nam. Yes, I say that, I the former protestor who tried to stop them from going. I never cursed or name called returning vets, then or now. Something some FNG-Posters can not claim.<br><br>
Steven Lane, if calling me playground names make you feel better, than please do it more often.  Hell, I won't even send you a bill. But before you embarass yourself any more, go back and read prior posts. I have been on this site almost from the beginning last November. Back then I thought all nam vets were homeless-freeway on ramp-bums-with phony PTSD cases looking for a hand out.  Thanks to many of the Vets I met in my early days, and their patience with me, I learned from them (and hopefully, I gave back a little). I learned that men like DocDel, Tanker, Tom, Gerald, Sarg, and Betty had stories to tell, to educate, and I had real faces to put on my thinking.  And they helped me see a picture far bigger than the one I had before this site.  Self Righteous? Oh you bet, but more so in the learning I have gotten here.  When you are &quot;up to speed&quot;, and not a FNG, and acting like a FNG, that we can talk.  But as for now, we speak in different languages.<br><br>
Michael Bender - Got to disagree. WW2 had protestors and those that disagreed, but it was clearly a case of evil (nazi's) versus the survival of our own country. Viet Nam was never a threat to the USA, was never considered as an &quot;evil&quot; and never had the heart of the people. That is why the voice of protest finally ended that fiasco. 58,000 Americans died, probably a million or two non american's, and I still say, it was wrong.  But they are dead, and I did what I believed to be right.  And I would do it again.  Please, don't compare WW2 to Nam, no more than you would want Nam compared with that parkinglot exercise called The Gulf &quot;war&quot;.<br><br>
Otto - Man what can I ever say to you?  Go call me a &quot;sick and guilty draft dodger&quot; is probably a tribute. To put me with Clinton (I am a Republican by the way) and Fonda is too bizarre for words.  You are quick with your words of cowardice and ignorance.  But try doing two things: (1). go back to the first posts in the archives and read, and hopefully think, and (2) try thinking for a change.<br><br>
Bill Clarkson - We are all here to communicate about Nam, and about our lives and the impact Nam had, be you vet or protestor.  Same comment. Scroll back and read foward.<br><br>
and lastly, &quot;azuren&quot;. Now here is a someone, a brave someone, who hides behind his keyboard without a name or e mail address and has the nerve to write: &quot;that you are a self-rightous bastered who was too fuckin' pussy to live up to the responcibilities of the whole situation.&quot; <br><br>
Well well, scratch being sensitive and politically correct. Again, you have not done your homework, not gone back and read and learned, just jumped into the middle and thought you know what was what.  Another FNG. (see, that is something I learned here). Perhaps when you learn to think, understand, and read, we will be able to share the contribution that I am sure you can make here. But, in the meantime, you demean the brave and decent men and women who died in that futile war.  If there be any cowardice here,<br>
it is you.  Had you gone back to find out who I was, and am, you would not still be drinking that wine of stupidity that thinks the &quot;spread of communism&quot; had anything really to do with Viet Nam.  Try reading a few other threads.  Try having the balls to spell out your name, or is it just &quot;hypocrite&quot;<br><br>
Self Righeous? Nope, but it is hard to be humble when you were and still are right. (those of you who know me will know why I wrote that, and the CFNG'S -cyberFNG's - will flame.   Flame on.  I am glad to be there for you.<br><br>
doc spatz
